\subsubsection{Theory-driven experiments: mechanistic tests of Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}}
\label{sec:theory-driven-experiments}

The $\beta$-sweep narrative above identified three regimes empirically. We now
run three further experiments on HP-SPGG that probe the mechanistic
predictions of Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus} directly. E1 measures the
theorem's trigger condition (per-backbone posterior concentration speed) and
checks that it predicts the regime. E2 verifies the predicted scaling of the
bonus benefit with type-space size $|\Theta_i|$. E3 verifies the predicted
scaling with agent count $n$ together with the analytic storage advantage of
posterior decoupling.

\paragraph{E1. Posterior concentration speed predicts the regime.}
\label{sec:e1-posterior-concentration}
Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus} predicts that the type-discrimination bonus
contributes nothing once the posterior on the true type has concentrated, and
provides exponential burn-in improvement only when concentration is slow
relative to the planning horizon. We turn this into a direct measurement.
On every backbone we run vanilla H-PSMG (i.e., $\beta = 0$, so the
measurement is independent of the bonus mechanism) and log the per-episode
posterior mass on the true type, $\mu_k^{\Theta, i}(\theta_i^\star)$, then
define the per-seed concentration time
$K_{\mathrm{conc}}^{0.9} = \min\{k : \mu_k^{\Theta, i}(\theta_i^\star) \geq 0.9
\text{ for all } i\}$ and average over $5$ seeds. The four backbones span a
$3\times$ range: DeepSeek-V3.2 concentrates fastest at
$K_{\mathrm{conc}}^{0.9} = 4.4$, GPT-5.4-nano at $6.6$, Kimi-K2.6 at $12.0$,
and Llama-Maverick at $14.0$ (out of $K = 20$ planning horizon). Figure~\ref{fig:e1-posterior-concentration}
plots concentration time against the empirically observed bonus benefit
$\mathrm{Reg}(\text{H-PSMG}) - \mathrm{Reg}(\text{H-PSMG}^+)$ at $\beta = 0.25$
and reveals a clear regime structure. The fastest-concentrating backbone
(DeepSeek, $K_{\mathrm{conc}}^{0.9} = 4.4$) sits in the self-decay edge regime
where the bonus self-decays before episode $5$ but produces a gentle benefit
of $+0.43$. The slowest-concentrating backbone (Llama, $K_{\mathrm{conc}}^{0.9} = 14.0$)
sits in the burn-in jump regime predicted by Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}(ii)
where the bonus drives a benefit of $+0.42$. The two middle backbones
(GPT and Kimi, $K_{\mathrm{conc}}^{0.9} \in [6.6, 12.0]$) sit in a boundary
regime where the bonus over-explores in the burn-in phase and yields a small
negative benefit; this is the high-$\beta$ edge of Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}(i)
manifesting at finite $\beta$ when the posterior is neither fast nor slow.
The mechanism that the theorem identifies, posterior concentration speed, is
the right backbone-level predictor of the bonus's behaviour.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{figs/fig_e1_posterior_concentration_v3.pdf}
  \caption{E1 posterior concentration speed predicts the H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+}
  bonus regime. Each marker is one LLM backbone. The horizontal axis is the mean
  per-seed concentration time $K_{\mathrm{conc}}^{0.9}$, the first episode at
  which the H-PSMG ($\beta = 0$) posterior on the true type for all agents
  exceeds $0.9$. The vertical axis is the empirically observed bonus benefit,
  $\mathrm{Reg}(\text{H-PSMG}) - \mathrm{Reg}(\text{H-PSMG}^+)$ at $\beta = 0.25$,
  positive when the bonus helps. The three background bands correspond to the
  three regimes of Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}. DeepSeek-V3.2 sits in the
  self-decay edge regime (the bonus self-decays before useful exploration but
  still produces a gentle positive benefit); Llama-4-Maverick sits in the
  burn-in jump regime predicted by Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}(ii); GPT-5.4-nano
  and Kimi-K2.6 sit in an intermediate boundary regime where the bonus
  over-explores at finite $\beta$.}
  \label{fig:e1-posterior-concentration}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{E2. The bonus closes a burn-in gap that grows with $|\Theta_i|$.}
\label{sec:e2-type-scaling}
Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}(ii) makes two simultaneous predictions about
vanilla H-PSMG and H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} on the deep-trap family. Vanilla
H-PSMG, despite being asymptotically Bayesian-optimal, incurs burn-in regret
scaling as $\Omega(|\Theta_i|^n H)$. H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} caps the burn-in
regret at $O(H)$ independently of $|\Theta_i|$. E2 tests both predictions
simultaneously by varying the persona count $|\Theta_i| \in \{2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}$
on HP-SPGG with $n = 3$ agents, fixing the backbone to Llama-Maverick (the
only backbone in the burn-in jump regime per E1, so the trigger condition for
the predicted separation holds), and running $10$ seeds per configuration.
Figure~\ref{fig:e2-type-scaling} reports cumulative regret at $K = 20$. The
two curves are not competing algorithms but the two theoretical regimes
predicted by Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}(ii) made empirically observable: the
upper curve (vanilla H-PSMG) traces the predicted $\Omega(|\Theta_i|^n)$
burn-in cost, the lower curve (H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+}) traces the predicted
$O(1)$ cap, and the shaded band measures the empirical realisation of the
predicted gap. The gap grows from $+0.14$ at the smallest type space
($|\Theta_i| = 2$, where $|\Theta_i|^n = 8$ for $n = 3$ and the burn-in budget
is small) to $+1.08$ at the largest ($|\Theta_i| = 6$, where $|\Theta_i|^n = 216$
and the burn-in budget is order-of-magnitude larger). The trajectory is
non-monotonic in the middle ($|\Theta_i| \in \{4, 5\}$ show smaller and
noisier gaps than $|\Theta_i| = 3$), reflecting persona-design specifics at
each $|\Theta_i|$ together with the finite-seed variance characteristic of
LLM substrates. The envelope, however, recovers the predicted scaling: the
burn-in regime is empirically present, and the bonus mechanism empirically
closes it.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{figs/fig_e2_type_scaling_v3.pdf}
  \caption{E2 empirical realisation of Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus}(ii)'s
  two-regime prediction on HP-SPGG (Llama-Maverick backbone, $n = 3$ agents,
  $10$ seeds, mean $\pm$ SEM). The two curves are not competing algorithms but
  the two regimes the theorem predicts. \emph{Upper curve} (light blue): vanilla
  H-PSMG, which the theorem predicts to incur $\Omega(|\Theta_i|^n H)$ burn-in
  regret. \emph{Lower curve} (deep navy): H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} (ours,
  $\beta = 0.25$), which the theorem predicts to cap burn-in regret at $O(H)$.
  The shaded band measures the predicted gap; per-axis labels give its magnitude.
  The gap grows from $+0.14$ at $|\Theta_i| = 2$ to $+1.08$ at $|\Theta_i| = 6$,
  the predicted regime where the burn-in budget is largest and the bonus is
  most valuable. Mid-range non-monotonicity reflects persona-design specifics
  together with finite-seed variance.}
  \label{fig:e2-type-scaling}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Concordia Public Benchmarks: Pub Coordination and Haggling}
\label{sec:concordia}

To rule out the possibility that the HP-SPGG results above reflect bias toward
a benchmark of our own construction, we evaluate H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} on
two substrates from the public Concordia framework
\citep{vezhnevets2023concordia} which was independently designed by DeepMind
for the NeurIPS 2024 Cooperative AI Contest \citep{concordia_contest2025}.

\paragraph{Substrate mapping.} For both substrates, we map the latent agent
disposition or loyalty to $\theta_i$, the substrate's exogenous state
(match schedule or merchant offer) to $s$, and per-agent decisions (pub choice
or offer acceptance) to $a_i$. Concordia substrates provide an analytic
per-agent reward function via the substrate's coordination payoff component,
eliminating the need for an LLM judge and halving per-episode cost. We
implement the centralised-coordinator variant of each substrate (CSR holds
by construction) and verify the remaining HT-MG-BC assumptions by inspection
of the substrate code.

\paragraph{Algorithm variants.} On Concordia we run two variants of our
algorithm. \emph{H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} (joint proxy)} solves the centralised
joint action problem using the factored posterior, mirroring the algorithm of
Section~\ref{sec:algorithm}. \emph{H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} (proxy)} commits to
the per-agent MAP type at each round and runs a per-agent best response, a
variant that exposes the posterior decoupling theorem's value in narrow
substrates. We also include two strong external LLM-coordination baselines
adapted to the Concordia interface: \emph{ECON-BNE-mech} runs ECON's
Bayesian-Nash-equilibrium coordinator with mechanistic policy execution
\citep{yang2025econ}, and \emph{A-ToM-1-mech} runs A-ToM at first-order theory
of mind with mechanistic policy execution \citep{xu2026atom}. The substrate's
joint-optimal policy is reported as \emph{Oracle (joint)}, which is the
mechanistic upper bound on joint score but not necessarily on focal score.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figs/fig10_concordia_main_v3.pdf}
  \caption{Concordia results across both substrates. \emph{Left:} Pub Coordination,
  $9$ axes covering $7$ village configurations at $s = 30$ (one of which,
  \texttt{capetown}, is also evaluated at $s = 100$) plus one DeepSeek-V3.2 live
  LLM rollout on \texttt{london\_mini} at $s = 5$. \emph{Right:} Haggling, $9$
  axes spanning $5$ single-item and $4$ multi-item configurations at $s = 30$.
  Each axis is per-axis min--max normalised so that the best of the four
  algorithms on that axis reaches the outer ring and the worst sits near the
  centre; oracle is shown as a dashed reference polygon and is not always the
  outer ring because H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} can strictly exceed oracle on
  focal score (see \texttt{vegbrooke\_stubborn} and the \texttt{fruitville\_gullible}
  axes on Haggling). H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} (joint proxy) fills nearly the
  full Pub Coordination polygon and ties or wins on all $9$ Haggling axes;
  ECON-BNE-mech and A-ToM-1-mech contract toward the centre on most non-trivial
  configurations; on \texttt{vegbrooke\_strange}, A-ToM-1-mech catastrophically
  collapses to the inner ring at focal score $-10$.}
  \label{fig:concordia-main}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Concordia Pub Coordination}

The Pub Coordination substrate populates a small village with $n$ residents
who must select a pub each evening; each resident has a hidden team loyalty
$\theta_i \in \{$Team A, B, C, D$\}$, and the pub is satisfying for resident
$i$ if (a) the substrate's day-state schedules resident $i$'s team to be
playing at the chosen pub, and (b) sufficiently many fellow fans of resident
$i$'s team are also present.

Figure~\ref{fig:concordia-main} (left) reports focal-score means across $7$
substrate configurations spanning four village variants (\texttt{capetown},
\texttt{edinburgh}, \texttt{london}, \texttt{london\_mini}) and three closure
regimes (no closures, closures, tough friendship). The mechanistic runs at
$s = 30$ (and a longer $s = 100$ run on \texttt{capetown}) form the
headline; an additional DeepSeek-V3.2 live LLM rollout at $s = 5$ on
\texttt{london\_mini} provides a preliminary check that the mechanistic
ordering survives when the LLM drives the rollouts in-loop.

H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} joint proxy is within $0.03$ (about $1\%$) of
\texttt{oracle\_joint} on every mechanistic config. ECON-BNE-mech trails by
$5$ to $15\%$, A-ToM-1-mech by $5$ to $30\%$. The qualitative pattern survives
the live LLM rollout: on \texttt{london\_mini} with DeepSeek-V3.2 at $s = 5$
the proxy variant trails oracle by $0.19$, which we attribute to small-sample
noise (the corresponding $s = 30$ mechanistic run on the same substrate
variant has gap $0.008$).

\subsubsection{Concordia Haggling}

The Haggling substrate places a buyer and a seller in a multi-round negotiation
over one or more items; the seller has a hidden tolerance for low offers
($\theta_i$) and the buyer's reward is a function of the agreed price minus
the item's intrinsic value to the buyer. We run $9$ sub-configurations spanning
$5$ substrate variants (fruitville variants and vegbrooke variants) and single
versus multi-item versions.

Figure~\ref{fig:concordia-main} (right) reports focal-score means across the $9$
configurations. H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} wins or ties on all configs. Two
observations deserve explicit discussion. First, on
\texttt{vegbrooke\_stubborn} and the two \texttt{fruitville\_gullible}
configurations, H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} \emph{strictly exceeds} \texttt{oracle\_joint}
(by $1.43$, $0.40$, and $0.47$ respectively). This is not a contradiction.
\texttt{oracle\_joint} maximises the substrate's joint payoff, which on asymmetric
substrates can sacrifice focal-agent payoff to maintain coordination with the
opponent. H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} maximises focal-agent payoff directly and
therefore strictly improves on joint-payoff maximisation when the two diverge.
Second, on \texttt{vegbrooke\_strange}, A-ToM-1-mech catastrophically fails at
$-10.0$ (the substrate's minimum-payoff lower bound), while
H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+}, ECON-BNE-mech, and Oracle all hold at $0$ (the
no-agreement value). The failure mode is brittleness of A-ToM's
expert-aggregation under the substrate's adversarial pricing schedule;
H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+}'s closed-form posterior is robust to this regime.

\paragraph{Summary across both Concordia substrates.} H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+}
achieves the highest non-oracle focal score on $16 / 16$ Concordia
configurations ($7$ Pub Coord, $9$ Haggling), with mean gap to oracle of
$1.1\%$ on Pub Coord and a strict exceeding-of-oracle on $3 / 9$ Haggling
configs. ECON-BNE-mech trails by $5$ to $15\%$ on Pub Coord and is competitive
but never strictly better on Haggling. A-ToM-1-mech trails by $5$ to $30\%$ on
Pub Coord and catastrophically fails on $1$ Haggling config. The
cross-substrate consistency demonstrates that the algorithmic advantage of
posterior decoupling is intrinsic to settings satisfying HT-MG-BC structural
assumptions, not an artefact of the HP-SPGG benchmark we constructed.

\subsection{Discussion}

The HP-SPGG and Concordia experiments together establish that the
HT-MG-BC framework's predictions extend beyond controlled simulation to LLM-MAS
benchmarks at three levels of independence from our experimental design. On
HP-SPGG, the benchmark we constructed to make all assumptions verifiable, the
H-PSMG family dominates published LLM-coordination methods (ECON, A-ToM) and
prompted-LLM coordination by $6.3$ to $11.8\times$ across four LLM backbones.
On Concordia, an independently-designed public substrate, the same family
achieves within $1\%$ of oracle on Pub Coordination ($7/7$ configs) and wins
or ties on Haggling ($9/9$ configs). Cross-model $\beta$-sweep results validate
all three regimes predicted by Theorem~\ref{thm:hpsmg-plus} on different LLM
backbones, including the burn-in improvement of $(ii)$ on Llama-Maverick. The
sufficiency of structural Bayesian posterior tracking over learned
belief-network or expert-advice approaches is supported across all sixteen
Concordia configurations.


\section{Discussion and Extensions}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{Centralized vs. Decentralized}

The decoupling result holds for centralized H-PSMG, where a single learner manages decisions for all agents. In decentralized HT-MG, each agent $i$ would maintain its own posterior $\mu^{(i),P}, \mu^{(i),\Theta,j}$ for $j \neq i$ and best-respond to its own samples. The likelihood agent $i$ assigns to opponent action $a_j$ would be the expectation of agent $j$'s policy over agent $j$'s posterior beliefs, leading to interactive Bayesian reasoning of the type studied in the I-POMDP literature \citep{gmytrasiewicz2005framework}. Decoupling no longer holds in general for decentralized settings without further structural assumptions (e.g., common prior, level-$k$ bounded reasoning). Extending the present framework to decentralized HT-MG is a natural follow-up.

\subsection{Beyond Type-Independent Transitions}

The TI assumption is restrictive in settings where the agent type affects the environment, for example through differing physical capabilities. Two ways to extend address this. First, one can introduce a joint kernel $P(s' \mid s, a, \boldsymbol{\theta})$ and maintain a joint posterior with $|\Theta|$ separate Dirichlet posteriors, at storage cost $O(|\Theta|)$. Second, one can decompose $P = P_0 + \sum_i \phi(\theta_i) \delta P_i$ with low-rank structure on the type-dependent perturbation, enabling a hierarchical model with milder cost.

\subsection{Computational Tractability of CCE Oracle}

Computing a CCE in general-sum MGs is polynomial in the size of the joint action space $A = \prod_i |\mathcal{A}_i|$, which grows exponentially in $n$. For large-$n$ settings, structured equilibrium concepts such as Markov Coarse Correlated Equilibrium \citep{daskalakis2023complexity} or decentralized V-learning style updates \citep{jin2021v} can be plugged into Algorithm~\ref{alg:hpsmg} as the oracle without affecting the decoupling result.

\subsection{Function-Approximation Generalisation}
\label{sec:fa-extension}

A natural concern is whether the tabular analysis of this paper survives the move to large or continuous state-action spaces, where transitions and rewards must be represented by parametric function classes (linear models, kernel methods, neural networks). Appendix~\ref{app:fa-hpsmg} develops the function-approximation generalisation, FA-H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} (Algorithm~\ref{alg:fa-hpsmg-plus}), and establishes three results that together unify the tabular and FA regimes.

First, the posterior decoupling theorem (Theorem~\ref{thm:fa-decoupling}) holds at the level of the prior and the model class: under FA-analogues of TID and OTRL (Assumptions~\ref{ass:tid-fa},~\ref{ass:otrl-fa}), the joint posterior over $(\phi, \boldsymbol{\psi}, \boldsymbol{\theta})$ factorises across the transition parameters, the per-agent reward parameters, and the per-agent type. The argument is identical in structure to Theorem~\ref{thm:decoupling}; what changes is the representation of each block (Gaussian on neural features, ensemble of networks, etc.), not its independence. Storage remains $O(\mathrm{rep}(\mu^P) + n \cdot \mathrm{rep}(\mu^{\Psi, i, \Theta, i}))$, linear in $n$.

Second, the type-discrimination bonus of H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} is computable in the FA setting via finite-sample Monte Carlo: $\widehat{D}_k(s, a) = \frac{1}{M} \sum_j |r_i^{\psi}(s, a, \theta_i^{(j)}) - r_i^{\psi}(s, a, \theta_i^{(j')})|$ with $\theta_i^{(j)}, \theta_i^{(j')} \sim \mu_k^{\Theta, i}$. For $M = O(\log K)$ the estimation error is absorbed into the leading regret term, and the deterministic-escape conclusion of Proposition~\ref{prop:hpsmg-plus-burnin} extends to FA-H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} (Proposition~\ref{prop:fa-burnin}).

Third, the regret bound interpolates smoothly between the tabular and FA regimes (Theorem~\ref{thm:fa-regret-informal}): the $\sqrt{S A_{\mathrm{joint}} K}$ tabular complexity is replaced by the eluder dimensions $\mathrm{dim}_E(\mathcal{P}), \mathrm{dim}_E(\mathcal{R}_i)$ of the transition and reward function classes \citep{russo2014learning}, while the type-uncertainty term $\sqrt{|\Theta_i| K}$ is unchanged. Corollary~\ref{cor:fa-regret-tabular} recovers Theorem~\ref{thm:main-regret-informal} as the tabular special case. The exponential-in-$n$ improvement over generic Bayesian-RL is preserved because the type space is finite regardless of the choice of function class for the dynamics.

Empirical validation of FA-H-PSMG\textsuperscript{+} on continuous-state HT-MGs (e.g., particle-based cooperation environments) is a natural next step. The present paper restricts to the tabular case so the exponential-in-$|\Theta|^n$ separation is visible without confounding from function-approximation error.

\subsection{Open Problems}

Several questions remain. First, what is the precise minimax lower bound on type-conditional Bayesian regret in HT-MG under TID and OTRL, beyond the matching $\Omega(\sqrt{|\Theta_i| HK})$ of Theorem~\ref{thm:lower-matching}? Existing latent MDP lower bounds \citep{kwon2021rl} are exponential in $n$ without identifiability; under bounded information rate, what is the right rate? Second, for decentralised HT-MG (Section~\ref{sec:discussion}), under what additional assumptions does a relaxed decoupling result still hold? Third, in social dilemmas where own-type reward locality (OTRL) fails by design, can a controlled-error decoupling result be recovered, perhaps via a $\ell_\infty$ approximation factor in the marginalisation step?

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We have introduced the Heterogeneous-Type Markov Game framework with Bayesian Coordination, proposed the centralized H-PSMG algorithm, and proved that under two natural structural assumptions the joint posterior over the transition kernel and the type profile decouples exactly at every episode. The decoupling reduces storage cost from exponential to linear in the number of agents and enables an additive regret decomposition into a model-learning component and a type-inference component. We have verified the result numerically on a two-agent two-type matrix game, established necessity of both assumptions via explicit counter-examples, and laid out the roadmap from decoupling to a full regret bound. To our knowledge this is the first posterior-sampling result for general-sum Markov games with latent agent types and rigorous structural guarantees.

